        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the Khula procedure in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Khula is a Muslim wife's statutory right to dissolve her marriage through a Family Court without the husband's consent. The wife files a suit under the Family Courts Act 1964, attends a mandatory conciliation hearing, and upon refusing to reconcile, the court grants a dissolution decree within 3 to 6 months. The wife must return her Haq Mehr (dower) as Zar-e-Khula."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How long does a Khula case take in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "An uncontested Khula case in Karachi takes 3 to 6 months from filing to decree. Contested cases where the husband disputes terms or delays proceedings take 6 to 18 months. After the court decree, a mandatory 90-day Iddat period follows before the NADRA Divorce Effectiveness Certificate is issued."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can my husband stop me from getting Khula?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. A husband cannot legally prevent a wife from obtaining Khula in Pakistan. Under the Family Courts Act 1964 and subsequent amendments, Khula is the wife's absolute right. Even if the husband refuses to appear in court, the judge proceeds ex-parte and dissolves the marriage without his consent."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Do I have to return my Haq Mehr to get Khula?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, generally. Since Khula is wife-initiated, the wife must return received dower or waive unpaid dower as Zar-e-Khula in exchange for dissolution. However, if the husband is at fault (domestic violence, abandonment), courts may grant Khula without requiring full dower return."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Does Khula affect my child custody rights?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "No. Khula strictly dissolves the marital bond and has zero effect on your independent right to seek child custody (Hizanat). Custody is determined separately based on the welfare of the child, not the method of divorce. Mothers retain preferential custody for boys until age 7 and girls until puberty."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are the legal grounds for Khula in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The primary ground is deep-seated aversion toward the husband. Additional grounds include cruelty, domestic violence, failure to maintain for 2+ years, husband's disappearance for 4+ years, impotence, insanity, and imprisonment for 7+ years under the Dissolution of Muslim Marriages Act 1939."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the difference between Khula and Faskh?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Khula is wife-initiated dissolution where the wife returns her dower in exchange for release. Faskh (judicial divorce) is dissolution on specific fault grounds where the wife retains her dower rights. Khula requires no proof of fault. Faskh requires proving grounds under the Dissolution of Muslim Marriages Act 1939."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the legal procedure for Talaq in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Talaq (husband-initiated divorce) requires the husband to send written notice to the Union Council Chairman and the wife under Section 7 of the Muslim Family Laws Ordinance 1961. A mandatory 90-day reconciliation period follows. If reconciliation fails, the divorce becomes effective on the 91st day."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does a husband legally pronounce Talaq?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The husband must issue a written Talaq notice to the Chairman of the relevant Union Council and send a copy to the wife. Verbal-only Talaq without Union Council notification is not legally effective in Pakistan. The written notice triggers the mandatory 90-day reconciliation process."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the Iddat period after Talaq?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Iddat is a mandatory waiting period of 3 menstrual cycles or 3 calendar months after divorce during which the wife cannot remarry. During Iddat, the husband must provide full maintenance including housing, food, clothing, and medical expenses at the same standard as during the marriage."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What role does the Union Council play in divorce?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The Union Council receives the Talaq notice, appoints an Arbitration Council, and attempts reconciliation within 90 days. If reconciliation fails, the divorce becomes effective. The Council then issues the Divorce Effectiveness Certificate required by NADRA to update marital status on the CNIC."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a Talaq be revoked in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. A single Talaq can be revoked during the 90-day Iddat period through written notice to the Union Council. After the Iddat expires, the Talaq becomes irrevocable. After three separate Talaqs, the couple cannot remarry unless the wife completes Halala (marriage to and divorce from another person)."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What are a wife's financial rights after Talaq?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "After Talaq, the wife is entitled to full Iddat maintenance (3 months), all unpaid Haq Mehr (dower), return of personal dowry articles (Jahez), and child maintenance if she has custody. The husband must also pay outstanding maintenance arrears accumulated during the marriage."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the court marriage procedure in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Court marriage in Karachi involves three steps: executing a Free Will Affidavit before a Judicial Magistrate, performing the Nikah ceremony with a registered Qazi in the presence of two witnesses, and registering the marriage with the Union Council for a NADRA Marriage Registration Certificate. The entire process completes in 1 to 2 hours."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much does a court marriage cost in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A court marriage in Karachi costs between PKR 15,000 to 30,000 including lawyer fees, Magistrate affidavit charges, Nikah Khawan fees, and Union Council registration. NADRA Marriage Registration Certificate processing is an additional PKR 2,000 to 5,000."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What documents are required for a court marriage?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Both parties need original CNICs (or passports if foreign), six passport-sized photographs each, and two adult male witnesses with valid CNICs. If previously married, the original NADRA Divorce Certificate or spouse's Death Certificate is required. Foreigners need a No Impediment to Marriage certificate from their embassy."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the legal age for marriage in Sindh?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The legal minimum age for marriage in Sindh is 18 years for both males and females under the Sindh Child Marriages Restraint Act 2013. Age must be verified through a NADRA CNIC or B-Form. Any marriage below this age is a criminal offense punishable by imprisonment and fine."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Is a court marriage valid for spouse visa applications?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. A court marriage resulting in a registered Nikah Nama and NADRA Computerized Marriage Certificate is fully valid for spouse visa applications worldwide. The certificate can be attested through the Ministry of Foreign Affairs (MOFA) for international recognition."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can parents file an FIR after a court marriage?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Parents sometimes file false kidnapping or Zina FIRs against the groom after a court marriage. However, a Free Will Affidavit executed before a Judicial Magistrate prior to the Nikah legally neutralizes these charges. The lawyer can immediately petition the High Court to quash any false FIR."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Who gets child custody after divorce in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Under Islamic law, mothers have preferential custody (Hizanat) for boys until age 7 and girls until puberty. After these ages, courts apply the welfare of the child test. Fathers retain financial responsibility regardless of custody. Courts consider each parent's capability, moral character, and the child's preference."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Until what age does the mother get custody in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Under Islamic family law applied in Pakistan, the mother has preferential custody for sons until age 7 and daughters until puberty (approximately age 12-14). After these ages, the court determines custody based on the child's best interests and, for older children, the child's own preference."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a father take custody from the mother?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A father can petition for custody if the mother remarries (this can affect her Hizanat right), if she is found unfit due to proven neglect or moral turpitude, or after the child exceeds the Hizanat age. The court always prioritizes the child's welfare over either parent's claim."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How does a court decide child custody in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Pakistani courts apply the best interest of the child standard under the Guardianship and Wards Act 1890. Factors include the child's age and preference, each parent's financial capability and moral character, living environment stability, educational continuity, and the child's physical and emotional wellbeing."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the Hizanat right under Islamic law?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Hizanat is the Islamic legal right of a mother to physical custody of her minor children after divorce. It gives the mother priority custody for boys until age 7 and girls until puberty. Hizanat is distinct from Wilayat (guardianship), which remains with the father even when the mother has physical custody."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can an overseas parent get child custody in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. An overseas parent can file custody proceedings through a Special Power of Attorney holder in Pakistani courts. Courts consider the child's current living situation, the overseas parent's ability to provide, and whether relocation serves the child's welfare. Video testimony may be accepted."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is wife maintenance calculated in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Courts calculate maintenance based on the husband's income, assets, number of dependents, and the standard of living during marriage. Typical awards range from PKR 15,000-30,000 for incomes of PKR 50,000-100,000, and PKR 30,000-75,000 for incomes of PKR 100,000-300,000. Self-employed husbands may pay 25-35% of net profit."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a wife claim maintenance during Khula proceedings?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. A wife can claim maintenance for herself during the pendency of Khula proceedings and for her children both during and after Khula. Child maintenance is the father's obligation regardless of the divorce method. The wife's personal maintenance typically ceases after the Khula decree and Iddat period."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the child maintenance obligation of the father?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "The father is legally obligated to provide maintenance for his children regardless of who has custody. This includes food, clothing, housing, education, and healthcare expenses. The obligation continues until sons become self-supporting and daughters until they marry. Courts enforce compliance through salary attachment."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to enforce a maintenance order in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "If the husband fails to pay court-ordered maintenance, the wife can file an execution petition in the Family Court. The court can attach the husband's salary, freeze bank accounts, seize movable property, or even order arrest for willful non-compliance. Employers can be directed to deduct maintenance from salary."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can maintenance arrears be recovered retroactively?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Pakistani courts can award maintenance arrears from the date the husband stopped providing maintenance, not just from the filing date. The wife must prove the period of non-maintenance. Courts calculate the total arrears and may order lump-sum payment or installment recovery."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How is property inherited under Islamic law in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Islamic inheritance law in Pakistan distributes the deceased's estate among fixed-share heirs (Quranic shares) including spouse, parents, sons, and daughters. Sons receive double the share of daughters. The estate is distributed after settling debts and funeral expenses. A person can only bequeath up to one-third of their estate by will."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is a succession certificate and when is it needed?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "A succession certificate is a court document issued under the Succession Act 1925 that legally authorizes heirs to access the deceased's bank accounts, investments, insurance claims, and other financial assets. It is obtained by filing a petition in the Civil Court with the death certificate and heir information."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a woman inherit property in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. Pakistani and Islamic law guarantee women's inheritance rights. Daughters receive a fixed share (half of a son's share), wives receive one-eighth if there are children and one-fourth without children, and mothers receive one-sixth if there are children. Denying women their inheritance share is illegal and punishable."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to challenge an unfair will or forged inheritance deed?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "File a declaratory suit in the Civil Court challenging the authenticity of the will or deed. Request handwriting and signature forensic analysis. Under Islamic law, a will cannot deprive any legal heir of their Quranic share, so any such provision is automatically void to that extent."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How much does a lawyer cost in Karachi?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Lawyer fees in Karachi vary by case type. Court marriages cost PKR 15,000-30,000. Khula cases range from PKR 50,000-150,000. Civil suits cost PKR 75,000-300,000 depending on complexity. Most lawyers charge a consultation fee plus per-hearing charges. Contact MR Law Associates at 0336 3120798 for specific fee information."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is an Advocate High Court in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "An Advocate High Court is a senior lawyer licensed by the Provincial Bar Council to practice in both lower courts and the High Court. This designation requires years of verified lower court practice. An Advocate High Court can argue appeals, file constitutional petitions, and represent clients at trial and appellate levels."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can I represent myself in court in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes, you can appear in person in Pakistani courts. However, court proceedings require strict compliance with the Code of Civil Procedure 1908, evidence laws, and court-specific rules. A single procedural error can result in case dismissal. Professional representation significantly improves outcomes."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to verify if a lawyer is licensed in Pakistan?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Verify a lawyer's license through the relevant Provincial Bar Council (e.g., Sindh Bar Council). Check their enrollment number, practice standing, and any disciplinary actions. Licensed advocates must have a valid Bar Council enrollment card. Ask to see the lawyer's Vakalatnama (authorization) before engaging them."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Can a lawyer handle my case without me being physically present?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "Yes. By executing a Special Power of Attorney (SPA) through a Pakistani embassy or consulate abroad, you can authorize a lawyer to represent you fully in Pakistani courts. The lawyer can file cases, attend hearings, negotiate settlements, and execute court orders on your behalf without requiring your physical presence."
          }
        }
      ]
    },
